porters are shown for varying [Na1]i.

The I–V relationship for INaCa (Fig. 3 A) closely dupli-
cates the experimental findings of Matsuoka and Hilgemann
(1992). Several properties of INaCa are demonstrated, in-
cluding saturation of the current with increasing voltage and
increasing [Na1]i (inset), and a shift of the reversal potential
to more hyperpolarized potentials with increasing [Na1]i.
This shift implies that INaCa operates in its reverse mode
(bringing in Ca21 and extruding Na1 with 1:3 stoichiome-
try, generating a repolarizing current) for a longer duration
during the AP, shifting the balance in favor of Ca21 loading.
The model simulates the experimental behavior, including
the “jump” in current magnitude between 10 and 20 mM
[Na1]i
(arrow) and the saturation at high voltage
and [Na1]i.

